  <h2 id="whatIs"> What is a Late Entry? </h2>
  <p class="islet islet--light">All three events (a Birth, Marriage or a Death) are usually registered locally soon after they have occured and they will, therefore, appear in the GRO indexes for that particular quarter, or the quarter immediately following the event. The system of Civil Registration operates under rules that specify the maximum time frame in which each of these three events should be reported to the local Registry Office. Marriages are typically registered during the marriage ceremony, either at a religious service in a church, etc, or at a civil wedding in a registry office or other recognised place. Deaths are typically also registered within a short time frame due to the legal constraints of arranging funerals, which cannot proceed without a valid death certificate. Births historically tend to have the longest time-frame for reporting. </p>
  <p>Events registered later than normal, sometimes several months or years later, will appear in the GRO Indexes for the quarter in which they are registered with the local Registry Office. In such cases, the <strong>quarter in which the event should have appeared</strong> is often annotated with a special type of entry: which is a link to the Late Entry. This entry, depending on the time-period in which the event happened, may either be a hand-written link to the late entry; or a printed link. You will neeed to go to the <em>late entry</em> itself to obtain the indexed record of the event [ and to obtain a certified copy of the record.] [link to: Ordering Certificates].</p>
  <p>Alternatively, an existing entry registered in the normal time-frame might have needed to be changed. Examples being: a birth entry where the child was later baptised with names that differ from those given at the time of registration; or, the mother was unmarried at the time but later married the child's father; or to correct other information in the entry. In such cases, the existing entry is either left unaltered in the index and a link added <em>pointing </em>to the new entry; or the existing entry has a handwritten amendment, added in such a way that the original entry remains legible, linking it to the new entry. Note: the original entry is not removed or deleated, but the GRO will only supply a [certified copy of the record referenced by the amended entry.] [link to: Ordering Certificates]</p>

  <h3 id="lE-Pre1984"> An example of pre-1984 Late Entries </h3>
  <p> An example may help to illustrate a late entry:</p>
     <figure class="site">
  <%= image_tag 'LateEntry1.png?sha=c8de42568b33aaaa', alt: 'LateEntry1', title: 'LateEntry1', width: 454, height: 270 %>
    <figcaption> Figure 1: Extract from a page of the births Index for 1909, second quarter.</figcaption>
    </figure>
 <p class="push-half--bottom">In June-quarter of 1909 we have an entry which shows a handwritten addition (at the bottom of the column) of: </p>
  <p class="islet islet--bordered push-half--left">Smith, John, Liverpool, 8B, See M/31</p> 
  <p>which is a link to a Late Entry reference. This indicates that there is an entry in the March-quarter of 1931 that should have been recorded in this quarter; and that its <em>correct place</em> on the index page is between the two lines indicated by its insertion mark. (Note: the surname Smith is not visible on this extract).</p> 
  <p>Then in the March-quarter of 1931 we have:</p> 
  <figure class="site">
    <%= image_tag 'LateEntry2.gif?sha=817daf74bef8307e', alt: 'LateEntry2', title: 'LateEntry2', width: 100 %>
     <figcaption> Figure 2: Extract from a page of the births Index for1931, first quarter.</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <p class="push-half--bottom"> where we see that there is an late entry: </p>
  <p class="islet islet--bordered push-half--left">Smith, John, Liverpool, 8b, 154 </p>
  <p> (Note: the surname Smith is not visible on this line).</p>

  <h3 id="lE-Post1983"> An example of post-1983 Late Entries </h3>
   <p> Two of the changes that the GRO made from 1st January 1984 was to change from Quarterly to Annual indexes; and to list individual entries with their month of registration rather than quarter. </p>
  <p>So, if the Late Entry and the matching birth entries were registered in the same year and the given-names remain relatively unchanged the entries may appear on the same index page (as in these two examples). </p>
  <figure class="site">
     <%= image_tag 'Post-1983%20Late%20Entry.png?sha=555048bca1a77e95', alt: 'Post-1983 Late Entries', title: 'Post-1983 Late Entries', width: 100 %>
     <figcaption> Figure 3: An example of two sets of post-1983 Late Entry birth records from 1989. </figcaption>
  </figure>
 <p class="push-half--bottom">  In reverse order of listing: the second set consists of three entries all registered in May 1989 (<strong>05.89</strong>) and apparently linked to a Late Entry of the birth of a child <strong>Martin John Phillips</strong>, whose mother's surname was <strong>MCPHERSON</strong>. In terms of layout, this example is comparable with pre-1984 entries, although all its entries are printed. The first of these three entries is a link to the Late Entry registered in the July quarter of 1993 (<strong>J93</strong>). The second and third entries were also both registered in May 1989 (<strong>05.89</strong>). The second entry is a Supplementary Page number <strong>N5972</strong> and the third entry has a <em>normal</em> page number <strong>1986</strong>. FreeBMD does not currently have the images for 1993 birth records, but the GRO site has a matching entry in the July-quarter of 1993, indicating that this birth may have been registered or re-registered in 1993.</p>
 <p> Next, we consider the first set of entries in more detail. In this example the first four entries appear to be linked to a Late Entry: the registration of the birth of a child <strong> Marc Phillips</strong>, whose mother's surname was also <strong>Phillips</strong>. The Late Entry was registered the same year as the registration of birth and appears on the same page of the index. It can be seen that both the first and fourth records were registered in January 1989 (<strong>01.89</strong>). The first entry consists of a link to the September quarter (<strong>S89</strong>) and it also appears to tie up with the second and third entries which were registered in July 1989 (<strong>07.89</strong>), which falls in the September quarter. The second entry has the Supplementary page number <strong>K6628</strong> and the third entry has a <em>normal</em> page number <strong>1377</strong> but they both relate to events registered in July 1989 (<strong>07.89</strong>). The fourth line has a <em>normal </em>page number <strong>1381</strong> but it relates to a event registered in January 1989 (<strong>01.89</strong>) so this may be related to the entry in the first line. </p>
  
  <h2 id="assist">How does FreeBMD assist? </h2>
  <mark> This refers to FreeBMD, FreeBMD2 has not yet implemented this feature </mark>
  <p> FreeBMD, by correlating together the reference to the Late Entry with the Late Entry itself, provides important help when you are researching these entries. This enables information to be quickly retrieved and,
in the case of the late entry, identifies the LateEentry which would otherwise not be evident unless the certificate was ordered.</p>

